Introduction

This report shows how the allometric diet breadth model of Petchey et al. (2008) was fit to empirical food web data. The report is basic and unrefined (purely functional in purpose).

Empirical data

2008 Skipwith Pond

fw_name <- "Skipwith Pond"
skipwith2008.all.web.info <- readRDS(here(paste0("data/", fw_name, ".web.2008.RDS")))
Plot.matrix(skipwith2008.all.web.info$predation.matrix)
box()

Skipwith Pond data from Brose et al. (2008)

The Skipwith Pond food web data was downloaded from here and then processed (steps are not shown in this document). The food web is similar to that used in Petchey et al. (2008).

skipwith.openaccess.all.web.info <- readRDS(here(paste0("data/", fw_name, ".web.openaccess.RDS")))
Plot.matrix(skipwith.openaccess.all.web.info$predation.matrix)
box()

Fitting the model

Starting parameter values

The search algorithm can get stuck in local optima, so the search is started multiple times each from a different location in parameter space. Those starting parameter values are loaded from a text file:

ratio_initial_pars <- read.csv(here("data/ratio.initial.pars.txt"),
                               header = FALSE)

Fit model to 2008 Skipwith Pond data

Here the outcome is the same as in Petchey et al. (2008).

NM.RH.web_2008 <- NM.ratio(skipwith2008.all.web.info, ratio_initial_pars)
Plot.matrix(NM.RH.web_2008$web)
box()

Using 2008 parameter estimates

Using the 2008 parameter estimates gives the same results as in Petchey et al. (2008).

a_2008 <- 1.07e-11
ai_2008 <- -2.03
aj_2008 <- -2.04
b_2008 <- 4.70e-1

EHL_2008 <- Ratio.allometric.EHL(M = skipwith2008.all.web.info$species.sizes,
                           e = 1,
                           r.a = 1, r.b = b_2008,
                           a = a_2008, ai = ai_2008, aj = aj_2008,
                           n = 1, ni=-3/4)
web_2008 <- Get.web(EHL_2008)
Plot.matrix(web_2008)
box()

Compare.links(web_2008, skipwith2008.all.web.info$predation.matrix)
## [1] 0.1383285
